<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This species is a native of south-eastern Australia, but introduced into many countries for utilisation purposes (mostly as an ornamental shrub). It easily reproduces and, like other acacias, is often considered to be an invasive species (
<bibRefCitation author="Miller, J T" journalOrPublisher="Diversity and Distributions" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="848 - 860" refId="B6509274" refString="Miller, J T, Murphy, D J, Brown, G K, Richardson, D M, Gonzalez-Orozco, CE, 2011. The evolution and phylogenetic placement of invasive Australian Acacia species. Diversity and Distributions 17 (5): 848 - 860" title="The evolution and phylogenetic placement of invasive Australian Acacia species" volume="17" year="2011">Miller et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Luque, GM" journalOrPublisher="Biological Invasions" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="981 - 985" refId="B6509222" refString="Luque, GM, Bellard, C, Bertelsmeier, C, Bonnaud, E, Genovesi, P, Simberloff, D, Courchamp, F, 2014. The 100th of the world's worst invasive alien species. Biological Invasions 16 (5): 981 - 985" title="The 100 th of the world's worst invasive alien species" volume="16" year="2014">Luque et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In Tenerife, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Cactaceae" genus="Acacia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acacia dealbata" order="Cactales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="dealbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Acacia dealbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a naturalised shrub, although some records doubtlessly refer to 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. mearnsii" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="mearnsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. mearnsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead. The latter superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. dealbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="dealbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. dealbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is recognised by its green and shiny foliage (vs. foliage bluish-grey with lustrous leaflets), cream flowers (vs. bright yellow flowers) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F6510131" captionText="Figure 1. Acacia mearnsii, Tegueste, January 2019. Compared with A. dealbata, this species has a green, shiny foliage and cream flowers." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494334" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">1</figureCitation>
) and pods softly appressed grey-pubescent to velutinous (vs. pods glabrous). Furthermore, in 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. dealbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="dealbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. dealbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, there is only a single gland at the base of the pinnae, whereas in 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. mearnsii" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="mearnsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. mearnsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on at least some leaves, multiple glands are present between the pinnae (
<bibRefCitation author="Maslin, BR" journalOrPublisher="Plant Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="353 - 480" refId="B6509256" refString="Maslin, BR, Ho, BC, Sun, H, Bai, L, 2019. Revision of Senegalia in China, and notes on introduced species of Acacia, Acaciella, Senegalia and Vachellia (Leguminosae: Mimosoideae). Plant Diversity 41 (6): 353 - 480" title="Revision of Senegalia in China, and notes on introduced species of Acacia, Acaciella, Senegalia and Vachellia (Leguminosae: Mimosoideae)" volume="41" year="2019">Maslin et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In Tegueste, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Cactaceae" genus="Acacia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acacia mearnsii" order="Cactales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mearnsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Acacia mearnsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was probably initially planted a long time ago and now survives. In the same place, a single individual was also observed of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. decurrens" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="decurrens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. decurrens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see earlier).
</paragraph>
